%N A388301 a(n) is the number of steps to reach n again when the Sisyphus sequence (A350877) begins with n, or -1 if n is never reached.
%C A388301 a(127) > 5261947751483 and a(211) > 1261930000000.
%H A388301 Karl-Heinz Hofmann, <a href="/A388301/a388301.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n=1..1014, with missing entries > 10^9 noted.</a>
%e A388301 a(10) = 3 because 3 steps are needed to end up again at 10:
%e A388301 Step 1: 10 is even and 10/2 = 5;
%e A388301 Step 2:  5 is  odd and 5 + 2 (= first prime)  =  7;
%e A388301 Step 3:  7 is  odd and 7 + 3 (= second prime) = 10.
%o A388301 (Python)
%o A388301 from itertools import count
%o A388301 from sympy import nextprime
%o A388301 A388301 = []
%o A388301 for n in range(1,45):
%o A388301     m, prime = n, 0
%o A388301     for steps in count(1):
%o A388301         if m % 2: m += (prime:=nextprime(prime))
%o A388301         else: m //= 2
%o A388301         if m == n: break
%o A388301     A388301.append(steps)
%o A388301 print(A388301)
